<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.developer.icloud-services</key>
    <array>
        <string>CloudDocuments</string>
        <string>CloudKit</string>
    </array>
    <key>com.apple.developer.icloud-container-identifiers</key>
    <array>
        <string>iCloud.com.voltralive.app</string>
    </array>
    <key>com.apple.developer.ubiquity-container-identifiers</key>
    <array>
        <string>iCloud.com.voltralive.app</string>
    </array>
    <key>com.apple.developer.ubiquity-kvstore-identifier</key>
    <string>$(TeamIdentifierPrefix)com.voltralive.app</string>
    <key>com.apple.developer.healthkit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.developer.healthkit.access</key>
    <array/>
    <key>com.apple.developer.healthkit.background-delivery</key>
    <true/>
    <!--
        b49: RESTORED com.apple.developer.healthkit.access = <array/> (empty)
        and ADDED com.apple.developer.healthkit.background-delivery = true.

        Background and council-confirmed root cause of the b47/b48 fresh-install
        bug (no HK permission sheet, no app row under Settings → Health):

        Apple's App ID "HealthKit" capability bundles three entitlements as
        a single grant (verified 2026-04-28 from the developer portal (i)
        tooltip on the HealthKit row):
          • com.apple.developer.healthkit
          • com.apple.developer.healthkit.access
          • com.apple.developer.healthkit.background-delivery
        There is no portal sub-toggle to opt out of any one of them. Every
        provisioning profile minted against this App ID carries all three
        in its Entitlements allowlist (with .access = ['health-records']).

        Before b49 our app declared only com.apple.developer.healthkit = true.
        On iOS 17+ this profile/app mismatch causes the OS to silently reject
        the HealthKit registration on a fresh install — no permission sheet,
        no Settings → Health row — while still honoring sticky authorization
        from prior installs (which is why HR/kcal kept working on already-
        authorized devices and the bug looked intermittent).

        The fix:
          • .access = <array/> (empty array) explicitly declares "I have
            access to HealthKit clinical records but I'm using zero clinical
            types." Apple docs at
            developer.apple.com/documentation/bundleresources/entitlements/com.apple.developer.healthkit.access
            describe this empty-array form as the documented opt-in when
            HealthKit is enabled and Clinical Health Records are not used.
            No NSHealthClinicalHealthRecordsShareUsageDescription Info.plist
            string is required when the array is empty.
          • .background-delivery = true matches the actual behavior we wire
            up in HealthKitStore.enableBackgroundDeliveryForTypes(); profile
            allowlists this anyway, so we may as well declare it.

        The b46 entitlements comment that previously lived here described
        removing .access as a fix for the Health row missing in Settings.
        That diagnosis was wrong. Removing .access did not fix anything on
        fresh installs — it only appeared to work because all test devices
        had sticky HK authorization from earlier builds. b49 reverses the
        b46 change and adds the missing .background-delivery key so the
        app's declared entitlements match the profile's allowlist.

        Verification: after b49 ships, on a fresh install the system HK
        sheet must appear at first launch and VOLTRA Live must appear under
        Settings → Health → Data Access & Devices.
    -->
</dict>
</plist>
